body:
Why not use _isNotEmpty_? It does internally check for _hasNext()_ and should semantically fit, should it?

Although the behavior is a little bit strange to me in the following code

``` java
        ArrayList arrayList = new ArrayList();
        arrayList.add("Luke");
        arrayList.add( "Leia");
        Iterator<String> it = arrayList.iterator();
        while (true) {
            assertThat(it).isNotEmpty();
            String next = it.next();
            System.out.println(next);
        }
```

_java.util.NoSuchElementException_

I personally agree that the code extract of @AlexBischof should work.

Note that I haven't looked at the code of assertj in detail yet, but it looks to me that `.isNotEmpty()` just does something like this (and yes, I am quite sure that this is not how things work internally):

``` java
// "it" is the iterator here
public boolean isNotEmpty()
{
    try {
        underlyingIterator.next();
        return true;
    } catch (NoSuchElementException ignored) {
        return false;
    }
}
```

which in turn would trigger the `NoSuchElementException` in the code example.

Now, another important thing to bear in mind here is that an `Iterable` and and `Iterator` are not quite the same thing. An `Iterable` is supposed to produce a fresh `Iterator` each time you call its `.iterator()` method; but this is not quite the same thing as testing an `Iterator` in itself.

In other words, an `Iterator` produced by an `Iterable` is independent from any other `Iterator` produced by that same `Iterable`.

As such I believe that it is incorrect to "promote" the test of an `Iterator` to that of `Iterable`, and that dedicated assertions for `Iterator`s are worth considering.

For instance:

``` java
assertThat(iterator).hasNext();
assertThat(iterator).nextElement().is*();
// or even chain
```

Comments?

[Javadoc](http://joel-costigliola.github.io/assertj/core/api/org/assertj/core/api/Assertions.html#assertThat%28java.util.Iterator%29) states clearly that assertions on an Iterator will consume it in most of the case. It was an easy solution to provide `Iterator` assertions.

Having said that, I agree that checking that an Iterator has elements left should not consume it.  

@fge My gut feeling is that having specific `Iterator` assertions will require a lot of work if you want to support the richness of `Iterable` assertions.

I think that @fge is right, the best solution would be to have `Iterator` assertions that only deals with the `Iterator` API including `isExhausted`, `hasNext`. 

This will obviously be a breaking change but we can alleviate that by making `toIterable(iterator)` utility method a first class citizen (that is adding to `Assertions`, `WithAssertions` and `BDDAssertions`

@stovocor is that something you are keen to contribute ?

We could add an `asIterable()` method to convert the `IteratorAssert` to an `IterableAssert` and provide iterable assertions on the **remaining** elements, my only concern is that it should make it clear it is on the remaining elements! (maybe renaming it to `remainingElementsAsIterable()` ?).

@fge @AlexBischof @stovocor @PascalSchumacher thoughts ?

Navigational assertions like `assertThat(iterator).nextElement().isEqualto(...);` would be nice to have but are tricky to implement because of soft assertions proxying, I'd rather create a separate issue for them.
